# Conventional Commits

## Format

`<type>(<scope>): <description>`

## Types

- `feat` — new feature
- `fix` — bug fix
- `refactor` — code change that's neither feature nor fix
- `perf` — performance
- `docs` — documentation
- `test` — adds or fixes tests
- `build` — build system, dependencies
- `ci` — CI config
- `chore` — everything else (housekeeping)

## Rules

- Description in imperative mood: "add", "fix", "refactor", not "added".
- Header ≤50 chars.
- Body explains *why*, not *what*. Wrap at 72.
- Breaking change: `feat!:` or `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer.
- Reference brain notes in body when relevant: `Following adr-0008-data-access-repository-pattern-for-portability.`

## Examples (Baller App)

- `feat(find-a-game): add lock-with-code on private games`
- `fix(chat): debounce typing indicator`
- `refactor(supabase): extract realtime channel hook`
- `perf(map): isolate marker clustering above 200 markers`
- `docs(adr): accept ADR-0005 ranked vs unranked architecture`
- `test(game-repo): cover join concurrency edge case`
- `chore: bump flutter_map to 7.0.0`

## Anti-patterns

- "misc fixes", "wip", "updates"
- Sentence-case past tense ("Added thing.")
- Header > 50 chars
- No scope when scope is obvious


